    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:4e385183-7cb2-4c2e-8b99-ba6f404aa755",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is an energetic 8-year-old girl with bright brown eyes and long, dark hair usually worn in two braids. Today she appears visibly unwell — her cheeks are flushed, her eyes are glassy, and she is sitting quietly on the examination table, clutching a stuffed rabbit. She is dressed in a colorful school uniform, suggesting she was brought in directly after her mother picked her up from school.\n\n{patientName} has been complaining of a very sore throat for the past three days, making it painful to swallow food or even liquids. Her mother reports that she has had a fever reaching up to 39.4°C (103°F), along with chills, fatigue, and a noticeably reduced appetite. {patientName} says her throat feels \"like sandpaper\" and has been reluctant to eat anything more than warm soup and ice cream. She has also had mild headache and swollen, tender lumps on the sides of her neck.\n\nAt school, {patientName} is in the second grade and attends a crowded public primary school where close physical contact with classmates is unavoidable — she shares desks, participates in group activities, and regularly attends choir practice twice a week, where singing in an enclosed room with other children significantly increases her exposure to respiratory droplets and airborne pathogens. Her mother mentions that several of her classmates have been ill with similar symptoms over the past two weeks, suggesting a possible school outbreak. Outside of school, {patientName} enjoys drawing and painting, participates in a Saturday morning art class held indoors in a small, poorly ventilated studio shared by 12 children, and loves playing on the school playground with her friends. At home, she enjoys reading picture books and watching animated films with her younger brother.\n\n{patientName} lives with both parents and her 5-year-old brother in a suburban home. Her brother recently recovered from a upper respiratory tract infection two weeks ago, representing a direct household exposure. {patientName}'s diet is generally balanced with home-cooked meals, though she has a known fondness for sweets and tends to consume sugary snacks and fruit juices regularly — a dietary pattern associated with suboptimal immune mucosal defenses. Her mother also notes that {patientName} frequently stays up late on weekends watching films and attending sleepovers with friends, resulting in irregular and insufficient sleep that may impair her immune response.\n\nOn physical examination, her oropharynx reveals markedly enlarged, erythematous tonsils with patchy white exudates bilaterally. Bilateral tender anterior cervical lymphadenopathy is present. Breath sounds are clear, and there are no signs of respiratory distress. She is up to date with her vaccinations and has no chronic conditions."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:0b4f8ec1-c249-4d7e-9a8c-682eaea56351",
      "resource": {
